    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#olagnas?">ᚑᚂᚐᚌᚅᚔ</name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">ᚋᚐ<unclear reason="damage">ᚊ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ᚔ</supplied><gap reason="lost"/></w></persName> 
                </ab>
             </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl" xml:space="preserve" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#olagnas?">OLAGNI</name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MA<unclear reason="damage">Q</unclear><supplied reason="lost">I</supplied><gap reason="lost"/></w></persName> 
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
                    <note>As there is damage to both ends of the stone, we cannot be certain that there isn't something lost before the O of OLAGNI. As noted by Macalister (1945, 65), the H-surface is flaked away as far as the L.</note>
                </app>
                    <app n="2">
                        <note>Only three strokes of the Q of MAQI survive before the break at the other end.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>‘of Ollán son of …’</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>OLAGNI (OLAGNAS in the nominative) may correspond to Gaulish <foreign xml:lang="xtg">Ollognus</foreign>, containing the element attested later in Irish as <foreign xml:lang="sga">oll</foreign> 'great' (McManus 2004, 22).</p>
            </div>
